{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17496976","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17496976"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T09:00:39+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T09:00:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1449"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1449","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1449"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.1,0.29,0.43,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1449"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"100406"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1449","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1449"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1449"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82810"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"33"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"758"},{"type":"tags","id":"4963"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11636"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2552"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2724"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34511"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44898"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"100406","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/100406"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 46-year-old woman presents to her general practice complaining of dyspnoea and visual changes. On further questioning, she confirms that her visual changes consist of increasing blurriness of vision towards the end of the day. She also reports a 3-month history of 15 kg weight loss, general lethargy, weakness and night sweats. She does not use any medications, is a non-smoker and drinks about two glasses of wine at weekends.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears to be moderately short of breath and she has a positive Pemberton\u0027s sign. On examination of the cranial nerves, she is found to have bilateral ptosis and binocular diplopia which improves when she closes one eye.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA chest X-ray (image) is ordered and shows the following:\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hodgkin lymphoma","Non Hodgkin lymphoma","Bronchial carcinoma","Thymoma","Pituitary metastases"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe chest X-ray shows a well-defined mediastinal mass. Together with the clinical picture, the most likely diagnosis is a \u003Cstrong\u003Ethymoma\u003C/strong\u003E (malignancy of the thymus). The visual changes are likely due to myasthenia gravis, a paraneoplastic syndrome commonly associated with thymoma. The positive Pemberton\u0027s sign suggests thoracic outlet and superior vena cava obstruction, which is commonly associated with thymoma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThymoma and thymic carcinomas are rare tumours that arise in the anterior mediastinum, with thymomas being the most common, accounting for 47% of mediastinal neoplasms. They may be an asymptomatic incidental finding, related to compression of surrounding thoracic structures, such as shortness of breath or thoracic outlet obstruction; as well as paraneoplastic syndromes such as myasthenia gravis, which is present in as many as 50% of patients.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther possible presentations related to paraneoplastic syndromes include a pure red cell aplasia (5-10%), immunodeficiency (\u0026lt;5%) and thymoma-associated multiorgan autoimmunity, a phenomenon similar to graft-versus-host disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWorkup of a suspected thymoma should involve imaging with a CT or MRI scan for the staging of disease followed by a definitive tissue diagnosis. The biopsy will most often be an excisional biopsy, although those with high stage disease not requiring resection will have a core biopsy. Staging for thymoma is based on the Masaoka system.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETreatment is primarily based on complete surgical resection with or without adjuvant radiotherapy depending on staging.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EKey differentials for an anterior mediastinal mass include retrosternal thyroid, \u003Cstrong\u003Elymphoma\u003C/strong\u003E, mediastinal germ cell tumour or small cell lung cancer. While these presentations may cause systemic symptoms and localised thoracic compression - they are less likely to be associated with myasthenia gravis. In addition, these lesions are less likely to be so well defined as the mass seen on this chest X-ray. Other primary malignancies such as \u003Cstrong\u003Ebronchial neoplasms\u003C/strong\u003E as well as \u003Cstrong\u003Edistant metastases\u003C/strong\u003E are important considerations although this presentation is most consistent with thymoma.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The presence of Pemberton\u0027s sign is indicative of a mass lesion in the upper mediastinum."],"references":["Detterbeck FC, Zeeshan A. Thymoma: current diagnosis and treatment. Chin Med J (Engl). 2013;126(11):2186-91.","Safieddine N, Liu G, Cuningham K, Ming T, Hwang D, Brade A, et al. Prognostic factors for cure, recurrence and long-term survival after surgical resection of thymoma. J Thorac Oncol. 2014;9(7):1018-22."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82810"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1449"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"14629"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"14629","links":{"self":"https://a